Pilots are taught to follow the instructions given to them by the hijackers, as this is seen as the best method for maintaining life. It is likely that the terrorists instructed them to fly towards NYC, but at some point took over controls of the aircraft when it was deemed to be on a manageable flight path. Having said this at least 1 of the terrorists was in fact a qualified pilot, so it is possible, but unlikely that they flew them all the way.<br>
<br>
It was reported that the hijackers repeatedly told the crew that if they did not make any silly moves no one would get hurt. The hope of survival and the realisation that the hijackers were capable of killing was likely to cause fear and thus stop anyone from challenging them.<br>
<br>
It seems that the plane that went down before Camp D was a failed attempt, and it would be interesting to find out what happened (if we ever will). All i know is that if it was due to the pilot, he deserves to be branded a hero, for the saving of so many lives.<br>
<br>
The world has certainly changed now, and i expect a international unified effort to find those responsible and work to stop this sort of thing happening in the future. <br>
<br>
Again, my thoughts are with those who have lost family, friends and loved ones.<br>
